Vector3¶

represents point or position, velocity and scale. Note! Angular velocity can not be represented by this type, it should be represented by Transform. It is a class inheriting numpy.ndarray, so it is also ndarray.

In [1]:
import py3d
py3d.Vector3()
Out[1]:
Vector3([0., 0., 0.])
In [3]:
py3d.Vector3(x=1.2)
Out[3]:
Vector3([1.2, 0. , 0. ])
In [5]:
py3d.Vector3(x=1, y=3, z=-2.4)
Out[5]:
Vector3([ 1. ,  3. , -2.4])
In [7]:
import py3d
py3d.Vector3(x=1, y=3, z=-2.4, n=(2,))
Out[7]:
Vector3([[ 1. ,  3. , -2.4],
         [ 1. ,  3. , -2.4]])
In [9]:
import py3d

p = py3d.Vector3(n=(2, 3))
p.x = range(3)
p
Out[9]:
Vector3([[[0., 0., 0.],
          [1., 0., 0.],
          [2., 0., 0.]],

         [[0., 0., 0.],
          [1., 0., 0.],
          [2., 0., 0.]]])
In [10]:
p.y, p.x
Out[10]:
(array([[0., 0., 0.],
        [0., 0., 0.]]),
 array([[0., 1., 2.],
        [0., 1., 2.]]))

Out[11]:

         [[2. , 2. , 0. ],
          [0.1, 3. , 0. ]]])

Cross product¶

In [24]:
import py3d
py3d.Vector3(x=3).cross(py3d.Vector3(y=2))
Out[24]:
Vector3([0., 0., 6.])
In [26]:
import py3d
py3d.Vector3(x=range(3)).cross(py3d.Vector3(y=range(3)))
Out[26]:
Vector3([[0., 0., 0.],
         [0., 0., 1.],
         [0., 0., 4.]])

Dot product¶

Determine if two 2d vectors are perpendicular¶

if two 2d vectors are perpendicular, then their dot product must be zero

In [27]:
import sympy
x, y = sympy.symbols("x y")
a = sympy.Matrix([x, y, 0])
b = sympy.Matrix([-y, x, 0])
a.dot(b)
Out[27]:
$\displaystyle 0$
In [28]:
import py3d
a = py3d.Vector3([1, 2, 0])
b = py3d.Vector3([-2, 1, 0])
a.dot(b)
Out[28]:
array([0])

Interpolation¶

In [30]:
import py3d
v: py3d.Vector3 = py3d.Vector3.Rand(10).cumsum(axis=0)
py3d.render(v.as_line())
i = v.interpolate([0.5, 1.6, 8.2, 7.44], range(10))
py3d.render(i.as_point().paint(py3d.Color(r=1)))
Out[30]:
